However, we do note that the distribution differs noticeably from the expected Poisson shape. We will give an explanation for this in a moment.

ax.set_title("2D histogram of particle counts", fontsize=16)

fig.colorbar(img);

Above we have plotted a 2D histogram showing how the distribution of particle counts changes over time. The granularity is too low to make anything out in detail, but some kind of time-dependence is apparent, with evidence of periodicity. This gives a potential explanation for the unexpected shape of the distribution from before: if the background is Poisson at any given time but with a time-dependent mean, then the aggregate time-averaged distribution will not be Poisson. Assuming that this is what's happening, all we need to do to model the background is characterize how the mean varies with time. This is done in the next section.

For completeness, we also plot below the solar phase and earth longitude of the satellite over an arbitrary 10,000 second window, and find as expected that both vary linearly, completing approximately two full 360 degree rotations in the selected window.

Below is a 2D histogram zoomed in to a 30,000 second window, with the solar phase and longitude overlaid to look for correlations.

We see that the variation in background appears to be synchronized with the longitude of the satellite. In particular, the rate of events suddenly increases each time the longitude passes about 315 degrees, then gradually decreases over the next 90 minutes before repeating. We would thus like to examine the rate of events versus the longitude, but the fact that the abrupt changes in event rate do not align with the 360 degree/0 degree crossover in the longitude makes this inconvenient. As a remedy, we introduce a "longitude parameter" $\rho$ which is related to the longitude $l$, expressed as before in degrees, by

$$\rho = \frac{(l + 45) \% 360}{360}$$

We have chosen this formula so that $\rho$ varies from 0, when the event rate is highest, to 1, when the event rate is lowest. We can now create a new 2D histogram of particle counts vs $\rho$ with overlaid mean.

In [354]:
rho = ((long + 45) % 360) / 360

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(15,7))
h, xedge, yedge, img = ax.hist2d(rho, counts, [500,30], [[0, 1],[0,30]])

# find bin centers from bin edges
x = (xedge[1:] + xedge[:-1]) / 2
y = yedge[:-1]

means = np.sum(np.matmul(h, np.diag(y)), axis=1) / np.sum(h, axis=1)
ax.plot(x, means, color='red', linewidth=2, label="Mean")

ax.set_xlabel(r"Longitude parameter ($\rho$)")
ax.set_ylabel("Particle count")
ax.set_title(r"2D histogram of particle count vs $\rho$ w/ mean", fontsize=16)
ax.legend()

fig.colorbar(img);

At a glance, the mean appears approximately exponential in $\rho$, and indeed we find a very good fit with the following parameters:

$$\mu = \exp\left(-\frac{\rho - 0.4354}{0.2503}\right) + 5.698$$
In [355]:
def mean_test(x, xloc, yloc, scale):
    return np.exp(-(x - xloc) / scale) + yloc
    
[xloc, yloc, scale], _ = optimize.curve_fit(mean_test, x, means)
print(f"x loc: {xloc} \t y loc: {yloc} \t scale: {scale}")
mean_fit = lambda x: mean_test(x, xloc, yloc, scale)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(15,7))
ax.plot(x, means, color='r', linewidth=2, label="Real mean")
ax.plot(x, mean_fit(x), color='b', alpha=0.7, label="Fitted exponential")

ax.set_xlabel(r"Longitude parameter ($\rho$)")
ax.set_ylabel("Mean particle count")
ax.set_title("Fitted mean", fontsize=16)
ax.legend();

x loc: 0.4353505142436041 	 y loc: 5.698326498266152 	 scale: 0.25028063934508826

We thus model the background distribution at any given time as a Poisson distribution with mean $\mu$ as given above. This model is compared to the real distribution for various values of $\rho$ in the graphs below. (To get a large enough sample for these real distributions we take all data points which have a $\rho$ of within 0.01 of the chosen value.) We see that our model fits the real data very well, confirming our earlier hypothesis that the background is locally Poisson.

In [367]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize=(20,15))

width = 0.01
ps = [0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.7]
for p, ax in zip(ps, axs.flatten()):
    filtered = counts[np.abs(p - rho) < width]
    mean = filtered.mean()
    x = np.arange(0,30)
    ax.hist(filtered, x, density=True, label="Real distribution")
    ax.step(x, stats.poisson.pmf(x, mu=mean_fit(p)), where='post', label="Modeled distribution")
    ax.set_xlabel("Particle count")
    ax.set_ylabel("Probability")
    ax.set_title(f"$\\rho = {p}$")
    ax.legend()

fig.suptitle("Real vs modeled distributions at different longitude parameters $\\rho$", fontsize=16);

(4)¶

We are interested in the probability that the background would produce a particle count as high or higher than a candidate signal. Since the background depends on $\rho$, so too will the 5 sigma threshold. This dependence is graphed below. (To determine whether a 100 ms candidate event is significant, one would look at the longitude of the satellite at the time of the event, calculate $\rho$ from that, then look up the corresponding threshold on the graph below and compare it to the candidate.)

In [370]:
prob = stats.norm.sf(5)
p = np.linspace(0,1,5000)
threshold = stats.poisson.isf(prob, mu=mean_fit(p))

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(15,7))
ax.plot(p, threshold)
ax.set_xlabel(r"Longitude parameter ($\rho$)")
ax.set_ylabel("Particle count")
ax.set_yticks(np.arange(21,33))
ax.set_title(r"$5\sigma$ detection threshold vs longitude parameter $\rho$");

In the logarithmic histogram, we can clearly see a normal distribution at low brightness, corresponding to sensor noise, as well as a long tail of bright objects. First, we want to extract the parameters of this gaussian sensor noise. The long tail seems to begin above a brightness of about 2.5, so we will throw away all pixels brighter than this and fit a normal distribution to what remains.

In [239]:

However, we are not interested in bright pixels, we are interested in changes in pixel brightness. This means we will have a different background for each pixel depending on its "base" brightness. To determine these backgrounds we make two assumptions. First, we assume that no transient appears in multiple images, so we can get a signal-free background for a pixel simply by throwing away the brightest value that pixel takes out of the ten images. Second, we assume that the width of the signal noise does not depend on pixel brightness, so we only need to individually determine the mean of the background for each pixel, and can use the aggregate standard deviation calculated above (0.56) for all pixels.

candidate_ind_flat = np.arange(0,400000,10) + candidate_ind.flatten()
background_images = np.delete(images, candidate_ind_flat)
background_images.resize(200,200,9)
means = background_images.mean(axis=2)

We can see above that there are about 30 transients with a significance of 4 or higher, but only one which reaches the 5 sigma threshold. This is the pixel at (112, 58), which is dark in most images (mean brightness -0.1) but jumps to brightness 2.8 in the second image. Also of note is pixel (17,52), which has a mean base brightness of 10.1, indicating the presence a star, but jumps to brightness of 12.5 in image 6. This could indicate that some kind of transient event overlapped the star, or that the star itself flared in brightness. However, since this event only had a significance of 4.1 sigma, we also cannot rule out sensor noise as an explanation.

In fact, we must note that the significances listed above only considers each pixel individually, with no trials factor correction. Given that our search covers 40,000 pixels, the aggregate significance of the event at (112,58) is only 2.4 sigma. (That is, there is a 0.8% chance that sensor noise would produce a fluctuation as large as is seen at (112,58) or larger in at least one of the 40,000 pixels in the image.) In light of this, we cannot confidently claim a detection of any transient event from these data.

(4)¶

As noted above, I am searching for changes in pixel brightness, whereas my partner is searching for any bright pixel. In particular, a pixel which is consistently bright across every image would be a detection for him but not for me. This manifests in the fact that my background pdfs for each pixel are centered around the average "base" brightness of the pixel, whereas for him they are always centered around 0.
